# Multi-Source Signal Analysis Rules

## Source Processing
- **Gong calls:** Identify each participant as CUSTOMER or PROSPECT. Extract exact quotes, pain points, competitive mentions, buying signals.
- **Canny requests:** Note vote count, top voter companies, request age, current status.
- **Zendesk tickets:** Identify implicit feature requests (workaround patterns), count tickets per theme, note requester companies.

## Triangulation
- Cross-reference by feature/theme across all three sources
- Flag features that appear in ALL THREE sources as CRITICAL
- Flag features in TWO sources as HIGH
- Single-source signals are MEDIUM
- **Do not let "loudest in the room" alone decide.** Weight evidence by the factors below so prioritization reflects role, customer status, and value â€” not just volume.

## Prioritization factors (use when ranking strength)
- **Role:** Who said it matters. Use Gong participant `title` (and optionally `get_call_participants`): executive/decision-maker (VP, CTO, Director, Head of) > manager (Engineering Manager) > IC (Analyst, Developer). Same quote from a VP blocks more deals than from an IC.
- **Customer status:** Long-time or high-value customers outweigh one-off prospects when the ask is similar. Use **product server `lookup_customer`** by participant email (from Gong parties or Canny/Zendesk): if found, note tier (Starter/Pro/Enterprise), seats, renewal; if not found, treat as prospect. Prefer evidence from existing Enterprise/Pro customers over prospects, and from accounts with renewal or expansion potential.
- **Sales potential / deal context:** When available, factor in deal size or perceived value: tier (Enterprise > Pro > Starter), seats, or Canny voter company value (e.g. `monthlySpend` in Canny live). Deal-blocking language from a large prospect or strategic account raises strength. In real deployments this may come from CRM (e.g. Salesforce); in the demo, use product tier and Canny company data as proxies.

When building the cross-source table, note for each piece of evidence: **who** (role, company), **customer or prospect** (from lookup_customer), and **tier or value proxy** where known. Use that to break ties or upgrade/downgrade strength (e.g. single mention from Enterprise VP + deal-blocking = HIGH even if only one source).

